  {
    "id": "why-i-paint",
    "title": "Why a Banker Paints: Finding Colour After Closing Hours",
    "category": "My Hobbies",
    "date": "2026-05-14",
    "excerpt": "People are often surprised that someone who spends her day with spreadsheets spends her evenings with turpentine. Here's why the two lives feed each other.",
    "content": "People are often surprised that someone who spends her day with spreadsheets and loan files spends her evenings with turpentine and brushes. To me, the two lives are not opposites — they feed each other.\n\nBanking teaches patience and precision. A ledger must balance to the last rupee, and a watercolour wash must be timed to the last second before the paper dries. Both crafts punish carelessness and reward a calm hand.\n\nPainting, on the other hand, gives me the one thing a bank never can: a place where mistakes become texture. A drip becomes rain. A smudge becomes mist on the hills.\n\nIf you also have a demanding day job and think you have no time for art, start with thirty minutes on a Saturday morning. Keep a small sketchbook by your tea. The work will find you."
  },
  {
    "id": "watercolor-layering-tips",
    "title": "5 Watercolour Layering Tricks I Wish I'd Known Earlier",
    "category": "Painting Tips",
    "date": "2026-04-02",
    "excerpt": "Muddy colours ruined my first fifty paintings. These five layering rules changed everything about how I build a watercolour.",
    "content": "Muddy colours ruined my first fifty paintings. These five rules changed everything.\n\nFirst, let each layer dry completely before glazing the next. Touch the paper with the back of your finger — if it feels cool, it is still wet. Patience here is ninety percent of clean colour.\n\nSecond, work light to dark, always. Watercolour has no white paint worth trusting; your lightest light is the paper itself, so protect it from the first stroke.\n\nThird, limit each glaze to three pigments at most. Mixing four or more pigments on paper is how mud is born.\n\nFourth, use transparent pigments for layering — quinacridones and phthalos glaze beautifully, while cadmiums and ochres sit on top and go chalky.\n\nFifth, tilt your board about fifteen degrees. Gravity pulls the wash into an even bead and does half your blending for you.\n\nTry these on a simple three-layer sky and you will see the difference immediately."
  },
  {
    "id": "oil-vs-acrylic",
    "title": "Oil vs Acrylic: Which Should a Beginner Choose?",
    "category": "Painting Tips",
    "date": "2026-02-18",
    "excerpt": "The most common question I get at exhibitions. The honest answer depends on your patience, your workspace, and your budget.",
    "content": "The most common question I get at exhibitions is whether a beginner should start with oils or acrylics. The honest answer depends on three things: your patience, your workspace, and your budget.\n\nAcrylics dry in minutes. That means you can layer quickly, mistakes are cheap, and cleanup needs only water. For anyone painting at a kitchen table after work — as I did for years — acrylic is the kinder teacher.\n\nOils stay open for days. That slowness is their magic: you can blend a sky for an entire evening, soften an edge tomorrow, rethink a portrait next week. But they need ventilation, solvents, and patience while paintings take weeks to dry.\n\nMy advice: start with acrylics for six months to learn colour and composition cheaply, then buy a small set of oils — just a warm and cool of each primary plus white — and paint the same subject in both. You will know within two paintings which one is speaking your language."
  }
]
